{"title_page": "Laity", "text_new": "{{short description|Members of a religious organization who are not part of the clergy}}\n{{redirect|Layman|the community|Layman, Ohio|the surname|Layman (surname)|the butterfly|Amauris albimaculata{{!}}''Amauris albimaculata''}}\nIn religious organizations, the '''laity''' consists of all members who are not part of the [[clergy]], usually including any non-[[Ordination|ordained]] members of [[religious institute]]s, e.g. a [[nun]] or [[lay brother]].<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08748a.htm Laity] at the Catholic Encyclopedia</ref><ref name=\"free\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/lay+person |title=lay person&nbsp;\u2014 definition of lay person by the Free Online Dictionary, Thesaurus and Encyclopedia |publisher=Thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\n\nA '''layperson''' (also '''layman''' or '''laywoman''') is a person who is not qualified in a given profession or does not have specific knowledge of a certain subject.\n\nIn [[Christianity|Christian]] cultures, the term '''lay priest''' was sometimes used in the past to refer to a [[secular clergy|secular priest]], a diocesan priest who is not a member of a religious institute.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} The [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] uses the term \"Lay Priesthood\" to emphasise that local congregational leaders are unpaid. Terms such as ''lay priest'', ''lay clergy'' and ''lay nun'' were also once used in [[Buddhist]] cultures to indicate ordained persons who continued to live in the wider community instead of retiring to a [[monastery]]. The adjective ''lay'' is often used to describe someone of the laity.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word ''lay'' (part of ''layperson'', etc.) derives from the Anglo-French ''lai'', from [[Late Latin]] ''laicus'', from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''\u03bb\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2, laikos'', of the people, from ''\u03bb\u03b1\u03cc\u03c2, laos'', the people at large.<ref name=\"free\" />\n\nThe word ''laity'' means \"common people\" and comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03bb\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 (''laikos''), meaning \"of the people\".{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n[[Synonym]]s for ''layperson'' include: [[parishioner]], [[Religious belief|believer]], [[Society of Dilettanti|dilettante]], [[wikt:follower|follower]], member, [[wikt:neophyte|neophyte]], [[novice]], [[wikt:outsider|outsider]], [[proselyte]], [[wikt:Special:Search/recruit|recruit]], [[secular]], [[wikt:laic|laic]], [[layman]], non[[professional]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesaurus.com/browse/layperson|title=Layperson synonyms, Layperson antonyms|website=Thesaurus.com|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Everyday context ==\nThe phrase \"[[layman's terms]]\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Autism & Asperger's Syndrome in Layman's Terms. Your Guide to Understanding Autism, Asperger's Syndrome, Pdd-Nos and Other Autism Spectrum Disorders|publisher=Cranendonck Coaching|isbn=9789789079391}}</ref> is often used to refer to terms that apply to the everyday person, as can the term \"layman\" or \"layperson\" itself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baum|first1=Caroline|title=A Layman's Guide to the President's Jobs Speech: Caroline Baum|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-09-08/a-layman-s-guide-to-the-president-s-jobs-speech-caroline-baum|accessdate=3 April 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|date=8 September 2011}}</ref> In English law, the phrase \"[[the man on the Clapham omnibus]]\" is sometimes used to describe a hypothetical person who is reasonably educated and intelligent but has no special expertise in a specific business or profession.\n\n==Christian laity==\nIn the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and the [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches, anyone who is not ordained as a [[deacon]], [[priest]], or [[bishop]] is referred to as a layman or a laywoman.\n\nIn many Catholic [[dioceses]], due in part to the lack of ordained clergy, [[lay ecclesial ministers]] serve [[Parish (Catholic Church)|parishes]] and in the [[diocese]] as pastoral leaders, sometimes as ''de facto'' pastor in the absence of an ordained [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]].\n\n===Catholic Church===\n{{main|Catholic laity}}\nThe [[Second Vatican Council]] [1962\u20131965] devoted its decree on the apostolate of the laity ''Apostolicam actuositatem''<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_decree_19651118_apostolicam-actuositatem_en.html '&#39;Apostolicam actuositatem'&#39;]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref> and chapter IV of its dogmatic constitution ''[[Lumen gentium]]'' to the laity in a sense narrower than that which is normal in the [[Catholic Church]]. The normal definition of laity is that given in the [[Canon law#Catholic Church|Code of Canon Law]]:\n{{Quote|By divine institution, there are among the Christian faithful in the Church sacred ministers who in law are also called clerics; the other members of the Christian faithful are called lay persons.\n\nThere are members of the Christian faithful from both these groups who, through the profession of the evangelical counsels by means of vows or other sacred bonds recognized and sanctioned by the Church, are consecrated to God in their own special way and contribute to the salvific mission of the Church; although their state does not belong to the hierarchical structure of the Church, it nevertheless belongs to its life and holiness.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__PT.HTM Code of Canon Law, canon 207]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>}}\n\nThe narrower sense in which the Second Vatican Council gave instruction concerning the laity is as follows: \n{{Quote|The term laity is here understood to mean all the faithful except those in holy orders and those in the state of religious life specially approved by the Church. These faithful are by baptism made one body with Christ and are constituted among the People of God; they are in their own way made sharers in the priestly, prophetical, and kingly functions of Christ; and they carry out for their own part the mission of the whole Christian people in the Church and in the world.<ref name=LG31>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19641121_lumen-gentium_en.html '&#39;Lumen gentium'&#39;, 31]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>}}\n\nIn this narrower sense, the Council taught that the laity's specific character is secularity: they are Christians who live the life of Christ in the world. Their role is to sanctify the created world by directing it to become more Christian in its structures and systems: \"the laity, by their very vocation, seek the kingdom of God by engaging in temporal affairs and by ordering them according to the plan of God\".<ref name=LG31/> The laity are full members of the Church, fully share in Church's purpose of sanctification, of \"inner union of men with God\",<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P27.HTM Catechism of the Catholic Church, 775]. Vatican.va.</ref> acting with freedom and personal responsibility and not as mere agents of the hierarchy. Due to their [[baptism]], they are members of God's family, the Church, and they grow in intimate union with God, \"in\" and \"by means\" of the world. It is not a matter of departing from the world as the monks and the nuns do that they sanctify themselves; it is precisely through the material world sanctified by the coming of the God made flesh, i.e. made material, that they reach God. Doctors, mothers of a family, farmers, bank tellers, drivers, by doing their jobs in the world with a Christian spirit are already extending the Kingdom of God. According to the repeated statements of Popes and lay Catholic leaders, the laity should say \"we are the Church,\" in the same way that the saints said that \"Christ lives in me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blessedsacramentregina.ca/non-integration-mass-ministries/|title=You are being redirected...|website=blessedsacramentregina.ca}}</ref>\n\nLay involvement takes diverse forms, including participation in the life of the parish, [[confraternity|confraternities]], [[lay apostolate]]s, [[secular institute]]s, and [[Roman Catholic lay ecclesial movement|lay ecclesial movements]]. There are also [[lay ecclesial ministry|lay ecclesiastical ministries]], and where there is a [[priest shortage]], lay people have to take on some functions previously performed by priests.\n\n====Vatican II afterwards====\n{{See also|Theology of Pope Francis#Clericalism}} \nIn December 1977, \"A Chicago Declaration of Christian Concern\" was published. The declaration looked back a decade to the Vatican Council II with appreciation for its \"compelling vision of lay Christians in society.\" As the Declaration interpreted it, the Council viewed the laity's \"special vocation\" as being the \"leaven\" for the \"sanctification of the world\" in their \"secular professions and occupations.\" However, lamented the Declaration, the Council's vision has \"all but vanished\" from the church.\n\nThe Declaration was signed by forty-seven clergy, religious, and laity that included men and women in many occupations, and it served as the charter for the National Center for the Laity (NCL).<ref name=\"catholiclabor.org\">http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/A%20Chicago%20Declaration.pdf</ref> The NCL helps lay Catholics respond to their call to change the world through their daily activities and regular responsibilities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicreview.org/article/work/working-families/national-center-marks-30-years-of-helping-catholic-laity.|title=Catholic Review - Archdiocese of Baltimore|publisher=}}</ref> and it publishes a monthly online newsletter ''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World.''<ref>http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL.htm.</ref>\n\n''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World'' (January 2015) rejoiced that \"50 Years since Vatican II\" the increased lay ministry in parishes has \"brought fresh vitality.\" However, the newsletter lamented \"the neglect of formation for the lay apostolate in the world.\" \n\nPope Francis is quoted as confirming this lament. Priests tend to \"clericalize the laity\" and view their ministry as only \"within the Church,\" discounting their \"workaday\" ministry.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/Jan%2015.pdf</ref> From the start of his papacy Francis called for structural change in the Church which will foster the responsibility of the laity now held \"at the edge of the decisions\" by &nbsp;\"excessive clericalism\", and to \"create still broader opportunities for a more incisive female presence in the Church\". The \"missionary transformation of the Church\" is seen by some as \"the goal of this pontificate\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Pope:-A-missionary-and-pastoral-conversion-for-a-Church-open-to-changing-its-structures-29645.html|title=Pope: \"A missionary and pastoral conversion\" for a Church open to changing its structures|last=Pisano|first=Franco|date=November 26, 2013|website=www.asianews.it|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> with all the baptized becoming \"missionary disciples\",<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0PGODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=We+cannot+demand+that+peoples+of+every+continent,+in+expressing+their+Christian+faith,+imitate+modes+of+expression+which+European+nations+developed+at+a+particular+moment+of+their+history&source=bl&ots=lSdVh0G-cg&sig=ACfU3U1ApmSDUN3pevokImcOGW6F-ElZTA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjR1pyas5bjAhWFLs0KHcCmC50Q6AEwBHoECBIQAQ#v=onepage&q=We%20cannot%20demand%20that%20peoples%20of%20every%20continent,%20in%20expressing%20their%20Christian%20faith,%20imitate%20modes%20of%20expression%20which%20European%20nations%20developed%20at%20a%20particular%20moment%20of%20their%20history&f=false|title=Go Forth: Toward a Community of Missionary Disciples|last=Francis|first=Pope|date=2019-06-26|publisher=Orbis Books|isbn=978-1-60833-787-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=69m7DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA130&lpg=PA130&dq=pope+francis+and+the+missionary+impulse&source=bl&ots=uH027i-rxv&sig=8_g0-OF9lIfkbWU6WjWmp4zNFRY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf85-R39XXAhWDH5QKHTUtD0sQ6AEIkgEwFQ#v=onepage&q=pope%20francis%20and%20the%20missionary%20impulse&f=false|title=Pope Francis and the Future of Catholicism: Evangelii Gaudium and the Papal Agenda|last=Mannion|first=Gerard|date=2017-04-24|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-13274-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Orthodox===\nThe [[Orthodox Church in America]]'s web site has eleven articles regarding its Theology of Lay Ministries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology.|title=Accessed January 4, 2015.|publisher=}}</ref> The term \"lay ministries\" refers to all the \"people of God\" (from the Greek ''laos tou Theou'') including the ordained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/ministry-of-people|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Ministry of People|website=oca.org}}</ref> Thus, every Christian has a vocation to ministry. A minority are called to ecclesiastical ministries. The majority are called to serve God and their fellow human beings in some way in the \"everyday secular world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/finding-ones-vocation-in-life|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Finding One's Vocation in Life|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Orthodox Church's assertion that all Christians are \"appointed\" as ministers is based on Scripture (1 Peter 2:9<ref>http://biblehub.com/1_peter/2-9.htm.</ref>) and the [[Church Fathers]]. The ministry of the laity complements the ministry of the priest in their daily lives in their families, their communities, their work: \"in whatever circumstances they find themselves.\" The most important \"lay ministry\" can be done anonymously. What one's ministry is depends on the abilities of the person: \"landscaping, carpentry, writing, counseling, child care, sports, music, teaching, or just being a good listener.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/an-orthodox-vision-of-lay-ministries|title=Parish Ministry Resources - An Orthodox Vision of Lay Ministries|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\nThe relation within the laity as the \"people of God\" between those who are ordained priests and those not ordained is one of cooperation in three areas: (1) in the [[Liturgy]], (2) Church administration, and (3) service (ministry) to others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/lay-ministry-a-shared-responsibility|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Lay Ministry - A Shared Responsibility|website=oca.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/ministry|title=the definition of ministry|website=www.dictionary.com}}</ref>\n\nIn spite of the church's teaching about the ministry of the laity in the world, the church gives more recognition to ministry within the institutional church. The \"daily ministry\" of the laity in their work, in their homes, and in their recreation remains hidden. Priests may intend to support their parishioners' daily ministry, but their priority tends to be recruiting volunteers for the church's programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/ministry-of-laity-in-daily-life|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Ministry of Laity in Daily Life|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\n===Protestantism===\n\n====Anglicanism====\nAnyone who is not a [[bishop]], [[priest]], or [[deacon]] in the Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.episcopalchurch.org/glossary/lay-order|title=Don S. Armentrout and Robert Boak Slocum, editors, \"An Episcopal Dictionary of the Church, A User Friendly Reference for Episcopalians\" (Church Publishing Incorporated, 2000), s.v. \"Lay Order.\" Online at|publisher=}}</ref> In the [[Anglican]] tradition, all baptized persons are expected to minister in Christ's name. The orders of ministry are thus laypersons, deacons, priests, and bishops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.episcopalchurch.org/sites/default/files/downloads/book_of_common_prayer.pdf|title=''The Book of Common Prayer according to the use of The Episcopal Church, 1979 edition'', 855. Online at episcopalchurch.org|publisher=}}</ref>\n \nThe ministry of the laity is \"to represent Christ and his Church; to bear witness to him wherever they may be; and, according to the gifts given them, to carry on Christ's work of reconciliation in the world; and to take their place in the life, worship, and governance of the Church\".<ref>''[[The Book of Common Prayer]] according to the use of The Episcopal Church'', 1979 edition'' [http://www.episcopalchurch.org/sites/default/files/downloads/book_of_common_prayer.pdf 855. Online at episcopalchurch.org]</ref> Much of the ministry of the laity thus takes place outside official church structures in homes, workplaces, schools, and elsewhere. It is \"through their continuous participation in political, economic, educational, and kinship institutions\" that the laity \"powerfully influence the character of these institutions.\"<ref>Gerhard Lenski, ''The Religious Factor: A Sociological Study of Religion's Impact on Politics, Economics, and Family Life'' (Anchor Books, 1963, rev. ed.), Section on \"Religions Impact on Secular Institutions,\" 342-344.</ref>\n\nLaymen also play important roles in the structures of the church. There are elected lay representatives on the [[Church of England#Structure|various governing bodies]] of churches in the Anglican communion. In the [[Church of England]], these governing bodies range from a local [[parochial church council]], through [[Deanery]] Synods and [[Diocesan Synod]]s. At the topmost level, the [[General Synod]] includes a house of Laity. Likewise, in the Episcopal Church in the USA, the [[General Convention of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America|General Convention]] includes four lay persons from each [[diocese]] in the House of Deputies, and each diocesan convention includes lay delegates from the parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.episcopalarchives.org/pdf/CnC/CandC_2012pp1-10.pdf|title=Governance Documents of the Church - The Archives of the Episcopal Church|website=www.episcopalarchives.org}}</ref>  On the local [[parish]] level, lay persons are elected to a church council called a [[vestry]] which manages church finances and elects the parish [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]].\n\nParish musicians, bookkeepers, administrative assistants, [[sexton (office)|sexton]]s, [[sacristan]]s, etc., are all roles normally filled by lay persons. At higher levels, diocesan and national offices rely on lay persons in many important areas of responsibility. Often specialized ministries as campus ministers, youth ministers, or hospital chaplains are performed by lay persons.\n\nLay persons serve in worship services in a number of important positions, including [[verger]]s, [[acolyte]]s, [[lector]]s, [[intercessor]]s, [[church usher|usher]]s. Acolytes include [[torch]] bearers, [[crucifer]]s, [[thurifer]]s, and [[boat boy|boat bearer]]s. Lectors read the lessons from the Bible appointed for the day (except for the Gospel reading, which is read by a Deacon), and may also lead the Prayers of the People.\n\nSome specialized lay ministries require special licensing by the bishop: the ministries which require a license vary from province to province. In the Episcopal Church, there are six specialized lay ministries requiring a license: Pastoral Leader, Worship Leader, Preacher, Eucharistic Minister, Eucharistic Visitor, and Catechist.<ref>Canon 4, Title III, ''Constitution & Canons Together with the Rules of Order for the Government of the Protestant Episcopal Church in the United States of America'', Adopted and Revised in General Convention, 2006</ref>\n\n====Methodism====\n=====Lay servant ministry=====\n{{main|Methodist local preacher}}\nA very early tradition of preaching in the Wesleyan / Methodist churches was for a lay preacher to be appointed to lead services of worship and preach in a group (called a 'circuit') of meeting places or churches. The lay preacher walked or rode on horseback in a prescribed circuit of the preaching places according to an agreed pattern and timing, and people came to the meetings. After the appointment of ministers and pastors, this lay preaching tradition continued with [[Methodist local preacher|local preacher]]s being appointed by individual churches, and in turn approved and invited by nearby churches, as an adjunct to the minister or during their planned absences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/who-we-are/roots|title=Roots (1736\u20131816) \u2013 The United Methodist Church|first=United Methodist|last=Communications|website=The United Methodist Church}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Methodist Church]] recognizes two types of lay ministries. One is a \"lay servant ministry\" of (a) assisting or leading local church meetings and worship or of (b) serving as lay missioners to begin new work within the church that requires special training.<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920 \"Lay Servant Ministry,\" Part VI, Ch 1, Sec XI, \u00b6\u00b6 266-271 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref> The other type is the \"ministry of the laity\" in their daily lives.<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920.\u00e5 \"The Ministry of All Christians,\" Part IV, Sec II, \u00b6 127, \"The Ministry of the Laity,\" 95 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref>\n\nIn addition to being appointed by members of their local churches, local and certified [[lay speaker]]s of the United Methodist Church (more commonly in the United States) attend a series of training sessions. These training sessions prepare the individual to become a leader within the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unyumc.org/pages/detail/1239|title=Certified Lay Minister|website=unyumc.org|accessdate=January 1, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> All individuals who are full members of the church are laity, but some go on to become Lay Speakers. Some preachers get their start as Lay Speakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist-e-academy.org/training|title=Methodist e-Academy - Training|website=www.methodist-e-academy.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Uniting Church in Australia]], that was constituted in part from the [[Methodist Church]], persons can be appointed by the congregation as a Lay Preacher or by the regional Presbytery to conduct [[Eucharist|Communion]].\n\nA well-known lay preacher was the late [[King of Tonga|King]] [[Taufa'ahau Tupou IV]] of [[Tonga]].\n\nThe comparable term in the Anglican and Episcopal churches is ''[[lay reader]]''.\n\n=====Ministry of the laity=====\nThe Methodist ''Book of Discipline'' describes the \"Ministry of the Laity\" in their daily lives as being \"Christ-like examples of everyday living\" and \"sharing their own faith experiences.\"<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920 \"The Ministry of All Christians,\" Part IV, Sec II, \u00b6 127, \"The Ministry of the Laity,\" 95 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref>\n\n=====Worship Leader=====\nIn the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain]], a Worship Leader is a trained lay person appointed by a Church Council to \"take a leading and significant role in the conduct of worship within the life of a Local Church\".<ref>Constutitional Practice and Discipline of the Methodist Church, Book III: Standing Orders, section 68: Worship Leaders</ref>\n\n====Presbyterianism====\nPresbyterians do not use the term \"lay\".  Thus the [[Church of Scotland]] has \"Readers\", men and women set apart by [[presbyterian polity|presbyteries]] to conduct public worship.  This arises out of the belief in the [[priesthood of all believers]].  Ministers are officially 'teaching elders' alongside the 'ruling elders' of the [[Kirk Session]] and have equivalent status, regardless of any other office.  In the Church of Scotland, as the Established church in Scotland, this gives ruling elders in congregations the same status as Queen's chaplains, professors of theology and other highly qualified ministers.  All are humble servants of the people in the congregation and parish.\nMinisters are simply men and women whose gift is for their role in teaching and possibly pastoral work. They are thus selected for advanced theological education.  All elders (teaching and ruling) in meetings of Session, Presbytery, or Assembly are subject to the Moderator, who may or may not be a minister but is always an elder.\n\n===The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints===\n{{main|Priesthood (LDS Church)}}\nMany leaders in [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] are lay ministers.  Essentially all male members above the age of 12 who are judged by church leaders to be in good standing are ordained to an office of the [[priesthood (LDS Church)|priesthood]] and hold various positions in the church. Most church positions at the local level are unpaid, but the LDS church helps with the living expenses of top church leaders and some others (e.g. [[mission president]]s). Many top church leaders serve in these positions after long secular careers. With the exception of members of the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve Apostles]], the [[First Quorum of the Seventy]] who are at the top of the church hierarchy, and [[Patriarch (Latter Day Saints)|patriarchs]], all leadership positions are temporary.\n\n==Buddhist lay persons==\n{{main|Householder (Buddhism)}}\nIn [[Buddhism]], a layperson is known as an ''[[upasaka]]'' (masc.) or ''upasika'' (fem.). Buddhist laypeople [[Refuge (Buddhism)|take refuge]] in the [[Three Jewels|Triple Gem]] (the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]], his [[Dharma|teaching]], and his [[Sangha (Buddhism)|community of noble disciples]]) and accept the [[Five Precepts]] (or the Eight Precepts) as rules for conduct.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090305011625/http://www.buddhanet.net/cmdsg/getting7.htm 7. The Five Precepts]. buddhanet.net</ref><ref>[http://www.experiencefestival.com/five_precepts_dictionary Five Precepts Dictionary | Global Oneness] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215145101/http://www.experiencefestival.com/five_precepts_dictionary |date=2013-12-15 }}. Experiencefestival.com. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>  Laymen and laywomen are two of the \"four assemblies\" that comprise the Buddha's \"Community of [[Sravaka|Disciples]].\"\n\nIn Chinese Buddhism, there are usually laypersons, who are depicted wearing a black robe and sometimes a brown sash, denoting that they received the [[The Five Precepts|pancha sila (Five Precepts)]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Faith at work==\nThe movement to help laity apply their faith to daily life has been divided into three eras by [[David W. Miller]] in ''God at Work''.<ref>Donald W. Miller, ''God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement'' (Oxford, 2006), Contents.</ref>\n:* The Social Gospel Era (c. 1890s\u20141945)\n:* The Ministry of the Laity Era (c.1946\u20141985)\n:* The Faith at Work Era (c. 1985\u2014Present)\n\n===Social Gospel===\nThe [[Social Gospel]] sought to reform society by the application of biblical principles. Its major proponents were all clergy: [[Washington Gladden]], [[Charles Monroe Sheldon]], and [[Walter Rauschenbusch]]. They were better in diagnosing society's ills than finding remedies.<ref>Ronald Cedric White, Charles Howard Hopkins, ''The Social Gospel: Religion and Reform in Changing America'' (Temple University, 1976). xviii.</ref> The Social Gospel reached its peak just prior to World War I, a war that contradicted its optimism about Christianizing society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldvieweyes.org/strauss-docs.html|title=WorldViewEyes -> strauss-docs|website=www.worldvieweyes.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Social Gospel was promulgated by the preaching, writing, and other efforts of clergy on behalf of the laity rather than by the laity themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ushistory.org/us/38e.asp|title=Religious Revival: The \"Social Gospel\" [ushistory.org]|first=|last=ushistory.org|website=www.ushistory.org}}</ref> In the early 1930s, the Social Gospel was described as \"a preacher's gospel.  It has not been the church's gospel. The laity have little share in it.\" Many were not aware what their clergy believed.<ref>Charles C. Morrison  ''The Social Gospel and The Christian Cultus,'' (Harper & Brothers, 1933), 42.</ref>\n\nMost scholars hold that the Social Gospel movement peaked between 1900 and World War I. There is less agreement about when and why the decline happened.<ref>[https://www.boundless.com/u-s-history/textbooks/boundless-u-s-history-textbook/the-gilded-age-1870-1900-20/urban-reform-153/the-social-gospel-818-9270/ Boundless. \"The Social Gospel.\" ''Boundless U.S. History''. Boundless, 14 Nov. 2014. Retrieved 16 Jan. 2015 from boundless.com]</ref>\n\n===Ministry of the Laity===\nThe Ministry of the Laity in daily life premise was stated by Howard Grimes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talbot.edu/ce20/educators/protestant/lewis_grimes/|title=Lewis Howard Grimes|website=Biola University}}</ref> in his ''The Rebirth of the Laity''.\n\"Although it is not alone through our daily work that we exercise our call, there is a special sense in which we do so in that area, since so much of our lives are spent in our occupations as lawyer, doctor, manual laborer, skilled craftsmen, housewife, domestic servant, student, serviceman.\"<ref>Howard Grimes, ''The Rebirth of the Laity'' (Abingdon, 1962), 95.</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Dean Reber of the [[Auburn Theological Seminary]] wrote a retrospective of the Ministry of the Laity era based on research and survey. His research participants were women and men in equal numbers, aged 20 to 60, from six denominations. Reber found that \"all were really interested to link faith with their daily life and work.\" However, in his survey, Reber found that little had been done in the six denominations to enable laity to make this link. He observed a \"preoccupation with activities inside the church,\" as well as a lack of literature and programs on the subject. For these reasons, attempts to link faith and daily life \"fizzled out.\"<ref>Robert E. Reber, \"Vocation and Vision: a New Look at the Ministry of the Laity\" in ''Religious Education: the official journal of the Religious Education Association'', 83:3, 1988. 402-411.</ref>\n\nFor Miller, \"hindsight suggests that the institutional church and its leaders never fully embraced or understood lay ministry\". Therefore, they stopped promoting the \"ministry of the laity\" concept to their members.<ref>Donald W. Miller, ''God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement'' (Oxford University Press, USA, 2006), 47.</ref>\n\n===Faith at Work===\nMiller deems \"Faith at Work\" to be \"a bona fide social movement and here to stay.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/God-Work-History-Promise-Movement-ebook/dp/B00OPJ8QOY/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1420320145&sr=1-1&keywords=9780199886234|title=God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement|first=search|last=results|date=14 December 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Amazon}}</ref> Unlike earlier movements, business people (from evangelical and mainline Protestant denominations, Roman Catholics, Jews, Buddhists, and unaffiliated) initiated the faith at work movement and support it because they want to connect their work and their faith. Management training often includes a faith dimension.<ref>Laura Nash and Scott McLennan, ''Church on Sunday, Work on Monday'' (Jossey-Bass, 2001), xxi-xxiv.</ref>\n\nExamples of various kinds of faith at work initiatives follow:\n\n* The Theology of Work Project is an independent international organization that produces materials for \"workplace Christians\" to teach them what the Bible and the Christian faith can contribute to ordinary work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theologyofwork.org/about/|title=About - Theology of Work|first=Theology of|last=Work|website=www.theologyofwork.org}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The National Center for the Laity (NCL) grew out of the 1977 \"A Chicago Declaration of Christian Concern.\"<ref name=\"catholiclabor.org\"/> It propagates the [[Second Vatican Council]]'s teaching about laity's vocation as \"daily work.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/History%20of%20NCL.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923200855/http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/History%20of%20NCL.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-23 }}</ref> The NCL's primary voice is ''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World''. In its January 2015 issue, ''Initiatives'' listed worldwide initiatives taken by laity in connecting faith and work.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* C12 Group offers training laced with Christian principles for CEO/Owners by monthly all-day meetings led by former CEOs. In its name, \"C\" stands for Christ, \"12\" stands for its ideal training group size. Group membership costs up to $1,450 per month. Some 1,500 Christian CEO/Owners belong to C12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c12group.com/.|title=Home - C12 Group|website=www.c12group.com}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Princeton University Faith & Work Initiative develops resources regarding ethics and vocation at work. It disseminates its learnings by programs for students, academics, and leaders in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeton.edu/faithandwork/|title=www.princeton.edu/faithandwork/|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Industrial Christian Fellowship helps its \"members and others to live out their faith at their work\" by research and publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icf-online.org/|title=www.icf-online.org|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Christian Association of Business Executives (CABE) \"exists to Inform, Inspire and Influence Christian business people from all church backgrounds and all types of business, as they seek to live out their faith day to day.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cabe-online.org/|title=Home - Christian Association of Business Executives|website=Christian Association of Business Executives}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Workplace as a mission field===\nSome faith at work initiatives focus not on work itself but on the workplace as a \"mission field.\" In this \"business as missions\" concept, faith at work means \"reaching people for Christ in the marketplace\", people that career missionaries could not reach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/business-professionals-advance-gode28099s-kingdom/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118195643/http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/business-professionals-advance-gode28099s-kingdom/ |archivedate=2015-01-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/businessmen-view-marketplace-as-mission-field/|title=Businessmen view marketplace as mission field - Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary|website=swbts.edu}}</ref> For example, Member Mission \"teaches the baptized to see themselves as missionaries out in the world in each of their daily places\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.membermission.org/about-member-mission/|title=About Member Mission|date=6 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lay brother]]\n* [[Laypeople (disambiguation)]]\n* [[La\u00efcit\u00e9]]\n* [[Expert]]\n* [[Jargon]]\n* [[Mumin]]\n* [[Upasaka]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}} cool\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n=== Roman Catholic theology of the laity ===\n* Burkhart, Ernst and L\u00f3pez D\u00edaz, Javier (2010, 2011, 2013), ''Vida cotidiana y santidad en la ense\u00f1anza de san Josemar\u00eda'', 3 vols., Madrid: Rialp\n* {{Citation|last = Congar|first = Yves Marie-Joseph|title = Lay people in the Church: a study for a theology of laity|year = 1957|publisher = Christian Classics|ISBN = 978-0870611148|location = Westminster}}\n* {{Citation|last = Dani\u00e9lou|first = Jean Guenol\u00e9-Marie|title = Saintet\u00e9 et action temporelle|language = French|publisher = Descl\u00e9e|year = 1955|location = Paris-Tournai}}\n* {{Citation|last = Philips|first = G.|title = Le r\u00f4le du la\u00efcat dans l'\u00c9glise|language = French|year = 1954|location = Paris-Tournai}}\n* {{Citation|last = Spiazzi|first = Raimondo|title = La Missione dei Laici|language = Italian|location = Rome|year = 1951}}\n* Thils, G. (1946), ''Th\u00e9ologie des r\u00e9alit\u00e9s terrestres,'' Paris.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_INDEX.HTM The Code of Canon Law] (Roman Catholic Church)\n* [http://www.sacred-texts.com/asia/rsv/rsv08.htm The Religions of South Vietnam] in Faith and Fact: V. [[Buddhism in Vietnam]] (Section E. Definitions and Explanation of Buddhist Terms)\n* Tanner, S., [http://www.utlm.org/onlineresources/paidclergy.htm Do Mormon Leaders Receive Financial Support?]\n* Gibbs, M., [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222122712/http://vesper.org/vwp/wp-content/uploads/GibbsLectureStrongLaity3FLAME.pdf \"The Development of a Strong and Committed Laity\"]\n\n{{Catholic laity}}\n{{Christianity footer}}\n\n[[Category:Religious terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Members of a religious organization who are not part of the clergy}}\n{{redirect|Layman|the community|Layman, Ohio|the surname|Layman (surname)|the butterfly|Amauris albimaculata{{!}}''Amauris albimaculata''}}\nIn religious organizations, the '''laity''' consists of all members who are not part of the [[clergy]], usually including any non-[[Ordination|ordained]] members of [[religious institute]]s, e.g. a [[nun]] or [[lay brother]].<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08748a.htm Laity] at the Catholic Encyclopedia</ref><ref name=\"free\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/lay+person |title=lay person&nbsp;\u2014 definition of lay person by the Free Online Dictionary, Thesaurus and Encyclopedia |publisher=Thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\n\nA '''layperson''' (also '''layman''' or '''laywoman''') is a person who is not qualified in a given profession or does not have specific knowledge of a certain subject.\n\nIn [[Christianity|Christian]] cultures, the term '''lay priest''' was sometimes used in the past to refer to a [[secular clergy|secular priest]], a diocesan priest who is not a member of a religious institute.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} The [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] uses the term \"Lay Priesthood\" to emphasise that local congregational leaders are unpaid. Terms such as ''lay priest'', ''lay clergy'' and ''lay nun'' were also once used in [[Buddhist]] cultures to indicate ordained persons who continued to live in the wider community instead of retiring to a [[monastery]]. The adjective ''lay'' is often used to describe someone of the laity.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word ''lay'' (part of ''layperson'', etc.) derives from the Anglo-French ''lai'', from [[Late Latin]] ''laicus'', from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''\u03bb\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2, laikos'', of the people, from ''\u03bb\u03b1\u03cc\u03c2, laos'', the people at large.<ref name=\"free\" />\n\nThe word ''laity'' means \"common people\" and comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03bb\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 (''laikos''), meaning \"of the people\".{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n[[Synonym]]s for ''layperson'' include: [[parishioner]], [[Religious belief|believer]], [[Society of Dilettanti|dilettante]], [[wikt:follower|follower]], member, [[wikt:neophyte|neophyte]], [[novice]], [[wikt:outsider|outsider]], [[proselyte]], [[wikt:Special:Search/recruit|recruit]], [[secular]], [[wikt:laic|laic]], [[layman]], non[[professional]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesaurus.com/browse/layperson|title=Layperson synonyms, Layperson antonyms|website=Thesaurus.com|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Everyday context ==\nThe phrase \"[[layman's terms]]\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Autism & Asperger's Syndrome in Layman's Terms. Your Guide to Understanding Autism, Asperger's Syndrome, Pdd-Nos and Other Autism Spectrum Disorders|publisher=Cranendonck Coaching|isbn=9789789079391}}</ref> is often used to refer to terms that apply to the everyday person, as can the term \"layman\" or \"layperson\" itself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baum|first1=Caroline|title=A Layman's Guide to the President's Jobs Speech: Caroline Baum|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-09-08/a-layman-s-guide-to-the-president-s-jobs-speech-caroline-baum|accessdate=3 April 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|date=8 September 2011}}</ref> In English law, the phrase \"[[the man on the Clapham omnibus]]\" is sometimes used to describe a hypothetical person who is reasonably educated and intelligent but has no special expertise in a specific business or profession.\n\n==Christian laity==\nIn the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and the [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches, anyone who is not ordained as a [[deacon]], [[priest]], or [[bishop]] is referred to as a layman or a laywoman.\n\nIn many Catholic [[dioceses]], due in part to the lack of ordained clergy, [[lay ecclesial ministers]] serve [[Parish (Catholic Church)|parishes]] and in the [[diocese]] as pastoral leaders, sometimes as ''de facto'' pastor in the absence of an ordained [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]].\n\n===Catholic Church===\n{{main|Catholic laity}}\nThe [[Second Vatican Council]] [1962\u20131965] devoted its decree on the apostolate of the laity ''Apostolicam actuositatem''<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_decree_19651118_apostolicam-actuositatem_en.html '&#39;Apostolicam actuositatem'&#39;]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref> and chapter IV of its dogmatic constitution ''[[Lumen gentium]]'' to the laity in a sense narrower than that which is normal in the [[Catholic Church]]. The normal definition of laity is that given in the [[Canon law#Catholic Church|Code of Canon Law]]:\n{{Quote|By divine institution, there are among the Christian faithful in the Church sacred ministers who in law are also called clerics; the other members of the Christian faithful are called lay persons.\n\nThere are members of the Christian faithful from both these groups who, through the profession of the evangelical counsels by means of vows or other sacred bonds recognized and sanctioned by the Church, are consecrated to God in their own special way and contribute to the salvific mission of the Church; although their state does not belong to the hierarchical structure of the Church, it nevertheless belongs to its life and holiness.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__PT.HTM Code of Canon Law, canon 207]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>}}\n\nThe narrower sense in which the Second Vatican Council gave instruction concerning the laity is as follows: \n{{Quote|The term laity is here understood to mean all the faithful except those in holy orders and those in the state of religious life specially approved by the Church. These faithful are by baptism made one body with Christ and are constituted among the People of God; they are in their own way made sharers in the priestly, prophetical, and kingly functions of Christ; and they carry out for their own part the mission of the whole Christian people in the Church and in the world.<ref name=LG31>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19641121_lumen-gentium_en.html '&#39;Lumen gentium'&#39;, 31]. Vatican.va. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>}}\n\nIn this narrower sense, the Council taught that the laity's specific character is secularity: they are Christians who live the life of Christ in the world. Their role is to sanctify the created world by directing it to become more Christian in its structures and systems: \"the laity, by their very vocation, seek the kingdom of God by engaging in temporal affairs and by ordering them according to the plan of God\".<ref name=LG31/> The laity are full members of the Church, fully share in Church's purpose of sanctification, of \"inner union of men with God\",<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P27.HTM Catechism of the Catholic Church, 775]. Vatican.va.</ref> acting with freedom and personal responsibility and not as mere agents of the hierarchy. Due to their [[baptism]], they are members of God's family, the Church, and they grow in intimate union with God, \"in\" and \"by means\" of the world. It is not a matter of departing from the world as the monks and the nuns do that they sanctify themselves; it is precisely through the material world sanctified by the coming of the God made flesh, i.e. made material, that they reach God. Doctors, mothers of a family, farmers, bank tellers, drivers, by doing their jobs in the world with a Christian spirit are already extending the Kingdom of God. According to the repeated statements of Popes and lay Catholic leaders, the laity should say \"we are the Church,\" in the same way that the saints said that \"Christ lives in me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blessedsacramentregina.ca/non-integration-mass-ministries/|title=You are being redirected...|website=blessedsacramentregina.ca}}</ref>\n\nLay involvement takes diverse forms, including participation in the life of the parish, [[confraternity|confraternities]], [[lay apostolate]]s, [[secular institute]]s, and [[Roman Catholic lay ecclesial movement|lay ecclesial movements]]. There are also [[lay ecclesial ministry|lay ecclesiastical ministries]], and where there is a [[priest shortage]], lay people have to take on some functions previously performed by priests.\n\n====Vatican II afterwards====\n{{See also|Theology of Pope Francis#Clericalism}} \nIn December 1977, \"A Chicago Declaration of Christian Concern\" was published. The declaration looked back a decade to the Vatican Council II with appreciation for its \"compelling vision of lay Christians in society.\" As the Declaration interpreted it, the Council viewed the laity's \"special vocation\" as being the \"leaven\" for the \"sanctification of the world\" in their \"secular professions and occupations.\" However, lamented the Declaration, the Council's vision has \"all but vanished\" from the church.\n\nThe Declaration was signed by forty-seven clergy, religious, and laity that included men and women in many occupations, and it served as the charter for the National Center for the Laity (NCL).<ref name=\"catholiclabor.org\">http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/A%20Chicago%20Declaration.pdf</ref> The NCL helps lay Catholics respond to their call to change the world through their daily activities and regular responsibilities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicreview.org/article/work/working-families/national-center-marks-30-years-of-helping-catholic-laity.|title=Catholic Review - Archdiocese of Baltimore|publisher=}}</ref> and it publishes a monthly online newsletter ''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World.''<ref>http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL.htm.</ref>\n\n''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World'' (January 2015) rejoiced that \"50 Years since Vatican II\" the increased lay ministry in parishes has \"brought fresh vitality.\" However, the newsletter lamented \"the neglect of formation for the lay apostolate in the world.\" \n\nPope Francis is quoted as confirming this lament. Priests tend to \"clericalize the laity\" and view their ministry as only \"within the Church,\" discounting their \"workaday\" ministry.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/Jan%2015.pdf</ref> From the start of his papacy Francis called for structural change in the Church which will foster the responsibility of the laity now held \"at the edge of the decisions\" by &nbsp;\"excessive clericalism\", and to \"create still broader opportunities for a more incisive female presence in the Church\". The \"missionary transformation of the Church\" is seen by some as \"the goal of this pontificate\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Pope:-A-missionary-and-pastoral-conversion-for-a-Church-open-to-changing-its-structures-29645.html|title=Pope: \"A missionary and pastoral conversion\" for a Church open to changing its structures|last=Pisano|first=Franco|date=November 26, 2013|website=www.asianews.it|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> with all the baptized becoming \"missionary disciples\",<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0PGODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=We+cannot+demand+that+peoples+of+every+continent,+in+expressing+their+Christian+faith,+imitate+modes+of+expression+which+European+nations+developed+at+a+particular+moment+of+their+history&source=bl&ots=lSdVh0G-cg&sig=ACfU3U1ApmSDUN3pevokImcOGW6F-ElZTA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjR1pyas5bjAhWFLs0KHcCmC50Q6AEwBHoECBIQAQ#v=onepage&q=We%20cannot%20demand%20that%20peoples%20of%20every%20continent,%20in%20expressing%20their%20Christian%20faith,%20imitate%20modes%20of%20expression%20which%20European%20nations%20developed%20at%20a%20particular%20moment%20of%20their%20history&f=false|title=Go Forth: Toward a Community of Missionary Disciples|last=Francis|first=Pope|date=2019-06-26|publisher=Orbis Books|isbn=978-1-60833-787-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=69m7DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA130&lpg=PA130&dq=pope+francis+and+the+missionary+impulse&source=bl&ots=uH027i-rxv&sig=8_g0-OF9lIfkbWU6WjWmp4zNFRY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf85-R39XXAhWDH5QKHTUtD0sQ6AEIkgEwFQ#v=onepage&q=pope%20francis%20and%20the%20missionary%20impulse&f=false|title=Pope Francis and the Future of Catholicism: Evangelii Gaudium and the Papal Agenda|last=Mannion|first=Gerard|date=2017-04-24|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-13274-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Orthodox===\nThe [[Orthodox Church in America]]'s web site has eleven articles regarding its Theology of Lay Ministries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology.|title=Accessed January 4, 2015.|publisher=}}</ref> The term \"lay ministries\" refers to all the \"people of God\" (from the Greek ''laos tou Theou'') including the ordained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/ministry-of-people|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Ministry of People|website=oca.org}}</ref> Thus, every Christian has a vocation to ministry. A minority are called to ecclesiastical ministries. The majority are called to serve God and their fellow human beings in some way in the \"everyday secular world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/finding-ones-vocation-in-life|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Finding One's Vocation in Life|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Orthodox Church's assertion that all Christians are \"appointed\" as ministers is based on Scripture (1 Peter 2:9<ref>http://biblehub.com/1_peter/2-9.htm.</ref>) and the [[Church Fathers]]. The ministry of the laity complements the ministry of the priest in their daily lives in their families, their communities, their work: \"in whatever circumstances they find themselves.\" The most important \"lay ministry\" can be done anonymously. What one's ministry is depends on the abilities of the person: \"landscaping, carpentry, writing, counseling, child care, sports, music, teaching, or just being a good listener.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/an-orthodox-vision-of-lay-ministries|title=Parish Ministry Resources - An Orthodox Vision of Lay Ministries|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\nThe relation within the laity as the \"people of God\" between those who are ordained priests and those not ordained is one of cooperation in three areas: (1) in the [[Liturgy]], (2) Church administration, and (3) service (ministry) to others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/lay-ministry-a-shared-responsibility|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Lay Ministry - A Shared Responsibility|website=oca.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/ministry|title=the definition of ministry|website=www.dictionary.com}}</ref>\n\nIn spite of the church's teaching about the ministry of the laity in the world, the church gives more recognition to ministry within the institutional church. The \"daily ministry\" of the laity in their work, in their homes, and in their recreation remains hidden. Priests may intend to support their parishioners' daily ministry, but their priority tends to be recruiting volunteers for the church's programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/resource-handbook/theology/ministry-of-laity-in-daily-life|title=Parish Ministry Resources - Ministry of Laity in Daily Life|website=oca.org}}</ref>\n\n===Protestantism===\n\n====Anglicanism====\nAnyone who is not a [[bishop]], [[priest]], or [[deacon]] in the Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.episcopalchurch.org/glossary/lay-order|title=Don S. Armentrout and Robert Boak Slocum, editors, \"An Episcopal Dictionary of the Church, A User Friendly Reference for Episcopalians\" (Church Publishing Incorporated, 2000), s.v. \"Lay Order.\" Online at|publisher=}}</ref> In the [[Anglican]] tradition, all baptized persons are expected to minister in Christ's name. The orders of ministry are thus laypersons, deacons, priests, and bishops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.episcopalchurch.org/sites/default/files/downloads/book_of_common_prayer.pdf|title=''The Book of Common Prayer according to the use of The Episcopal Church, 1979 edition'', 855. Online at episcopalchurch.org|publisher=}}</ref>\n \nThe ministry of the laity is \"to represent Christ and his Church; to bear witness to him wherever they may be; and, according to the gifts given them, to carry on Christ's work of reconciliation in the world; and to take their place in the life, worship, and governance of the Church\".<ref>''[[The Book of Common Prayer]] according to the use of The Episcopal Church'', 1979 edition'' [http://www.episcopalchurch.org/sites/default/files/downloads/book_of_common_prayer.pdf 855. Online at episcopalchurch.org]</ref> Much of the ministry of the laity thus takes place outside official church structures in homes, workplaces, schools, and elsewhere. It is \"through their continuous participation in political, economic, educational, and kinship institutions\" that the laity \"powerfully influence the character of these institutions.\"<ref>Gerhard Lenski, ''The Religious Factor: A Sociological Study of Religion's Impact on Politics, Economics, and Family Life'' (Anchor Books, 1963, rev. ed.), Section on \"Religions Impact on Secular Institutions,\" 342-344.</ref>\n\nLaymen also play important roles in the structures of the church. There are elected lay representatives on the [[Church of England#Structure|various governing bodies]] of churches in the Anglican communion. In the [[Church of England]], these governing bodies range from a local [[parochial church council]], through [[Deanery]] Synods and [[Diocesan Synod]]s. At the topmost level, the [[General Synod]] includes a house of Laity. Likewise, in the Episcopal Church in the USA, the [[General Convention of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America|General Convention]] includes four lay persons from each [[diocese]] in the House of Deputies, and each diocesan convention includes lay delegates from the parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.episcopalarchives.org/pdf/CnC/CandC_2012pp1-10.pdf|title=Governance Documents of the Church - The Archives of the Episcopal Church|website=www.episcopalarchives.org}}</ref>  On the local [[parish]] level, lay persons are elected to a church council called a [[vestry]] which manages church finances and elects the parish [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]].\n\nParish musicians, bookkeepers, administrative assistants, [[sexton (office)|sexton]]s, [[sacristan]]s, etc., are all roles normally filled by lay persons. At higher levels, diocesan and national offices rely on lay persons in many important areas of responsibility. Often specialized ministries as campus ministers, youth ministers, or hospital chaplains are performed by lay persons.\n\nLay persons serve in worship services in a number of important positions, including [[verger]]s, [[acolyte]]s, [[lector]]s, [[intercessor]]s, [[church usher|usher]]s. Acolytes include [[torch]] bearers, [[crucifer]]s, [[thurifer]]s, and [[boat boy|boat bearer]]s. Lectors read the lessons from the Bible appointed for the day (except for the Gospel reading, which is read by a Deacon), and may also lead the Prayers of the People.\n\nSome specialized lay ministries require special licensing by the bishop: the ministries which require a license vary from province to province. In the Episcopal Church, there are six specialized lay ministries requiring a license: Pastoral Leader, Worship Leader, Preacher, Eucharistic Minister, Eucharistic Visitor, and Catechist.<ref>Canon 4, Title III, ''Constitution & Canons Together with the Rules of Order for the Government of the Protestant Episcopal Church in the United States of America'', Adopted and Revised in General Convention, 2006</ref>\n\n====Methodism====\n=====Lay servant ministry=====\n{{main|Methodist local preacher}}\nA very early tradition of preaching in the Wesleyan / Methodist churches was for a lay preacher to be appointed to lead services of worship and preach in a group (called a 'circuit') of meeting places or churches. The lay preacher walked or rode on horseback in a prescribed circuit of the preaching places according to an agreed pattern and timing, and people came to the meetings. After the appointment of ministers and pastors, this lay preaching tradition continued with [[Methodist local preacher|local preacher]]s being appointed by individual churches, and in turn approved and invited by nearby churches, as an adjunct to the minister or during their planned absences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/who-we-are/roots|title=Roots (1736\u20131816) \u2013 The United Methodist Church|first=United Methodist|last=Communications|website=The United Methodist Church}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Methodist Church]] recognizes two types of lay ministries. One is a \"lay servant ministry\" of (a) assisting or leading local church meetings and worship or of (b) serving as lay missioners to begin new work within the church that requires special training.<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920 \"Lay Servant Ministry,\" Part VI, Ch 1, Sec XI, \u00b6\u00b6 266-271 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref> The other type is the \"ministry of the laity\" in their daily lives.<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920.\u00e5 \"The Ministry of All Christians,\" Part IV, Sec II, \u00b6 127, \"The Ministry of the Laity,\" 95 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref>\n\nIn addition to being appointed by members of their local churches, local and certified [[lay speaker]]s of the United Methodist Church (more commonly in the United States) attend a series of training sessions. These training sessions prepare the individual to become a leader within the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unyumc.org/pages/detail/1239|title=Certified Lay Minister|website=unyumc.org|accessdate=January 1, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> All individuals who are full members of the church are laity, but some go on to become Lay Speakers. Some preachers get their start as Lay Speakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist-e-academy.org/training|title=Methodist e-Academy - Training|website=www.methodist-e-academy.org}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Uniting Church in Australia]], that was constituted in part from the [[Methodist Church]], persons can be appointed by the congregation as a Lay Preacher or by the regional Presbytery to conduct [[Eucharist|Communion]].\n\nA well-known lay preacher was the late [[King of Tonga|King]] [[Taufa'ahau Tupou IV]] of [[Tonga]].\n\nThe comparable term in the Anglican and Episcopal churches is ''[[lay reader]]''.\n\n=====Ministry of the laity=====\nThe Methodist ''Book of Discipline'' describes the \"Ministry of the Laity\" in their daily lives as being \"Christ-like examples of everyday living\" and \"sharing their own faith experiences.\"<ref>[http://www.cokesbury.com/forms/DynamicContent.aspx?id=87&pageid=920 \"The Ministry of All Christians,\" Part IV, Sec II, \u00b6 127, \"The Ministry of the Laity,\" 95 of ''The Book of Discipline of the United Methodist Church, 2012'' (The United Methodist Publishing House, 2012). Online at cokesbury.com]</ref>\n\n=====Worship Leader=====\nIn the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain]], a Worship Leader is a trained lay person appointed by a Church Council to \"take a leading and significant role in the conduct of worship within the life of a Local Church\".<ref>Constutitional Practice and Discipline of the Methodist Church, Book III: Standing Orders, section 68: Worship Leaders</ref>\n\n====Presbyterianism====\nPresbyterians do not use the term \"lay\".  Thus the [[Church of Scotland]] has \"Readers\", men and women set apart by [[presbyterian polity|presbyteries]] to conduct public worship.  This arises out of the belief in the [[priesthood of all believers]].  Ministers are officially 'teaching elders' alongside the 'ruling elders' of the [[Kirk Session]] and have equivalent status, regardless of any other office.  In the Church of Scotland, as the Established church in Scotland, this gives ruling elders in congregations the same status as Queen's chaplains, professors of theology and other highly qualified ministers.  All are humble servants of the people in the congregation and parish.\nMinisters are simply men and women whose gift is for their role in teaching and possibly pastoral work. They are thus selected for advanced theological education.  All elders (teaching and ruling) in meetings of Session, Presbytery, or Assembly are subject to the Moderator, who may or may not be a minister but is always an elder.\n\n===The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints===\n{{main|Priesthood (LDS Church)}}\nMany leaders in [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] are lay ministers.  Essentially all male members above the age of 12 who are judged by church leaders to be in good standing are ordained to an office of the [[priesthood (LDS Church)|priesthood]] and hold various positions in the church. Most church positions at the local level are unpaid, but the LDS church helps with the living expenses of top church leaders and some others (e.g. [[mission president]]s). Many top church leaders serve in these positions after long secular careers. With the exception of members of the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve Apostles]], the [[First Quorum of the Seventy]] who are at the top of the church hierarchy, and [[Patriarch (Latter Day Saints)|patriarchs]], all leadership positions are temporary.\n\n==Buddhist lay persons==\n{{main|Householder (Buddhism)}}\nIn [[Buddhism]], a layperson is known as an ''[[upasaka]]'' (masc.) or ''upasika'' (fem.). Buddhist laypeople [[Refuge (Buddhism)|take refuge]] in the [[Three Jewels|Triple Gem]] (the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]], his [[Dharma|teaching]], and his [[Sangha (Buddhism)|community of noble disciples]]) and accept the [[Five Precepts]] (or the Eight Precepts) as rules for conduct.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090305011625/http://www.buddhanet.net/cmdsg/getting7.htm 7. The Five Precepts]. buddhanet.net</ref><ref>[http://www.experiencefestival.com/five_precepts_dictionary Five Precepts Dictionary | Global Oneness] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215145101/http://www.experiencefestival.com/five_precepts_dictionary |date=2013-12-15 }}. Experiencefestival.com. Retrieved on 2013-12-15.</ref>  Laymen and laywomen are two of the \"four assemblies\" that comprise the Buddha's \"Community of [[Sravaka|Disciples]].\"\n\nIn Chinese Buddhism, there are usually laypersons, who are depicted wearing a black robe and sometimes a brown sash, denoting that they received the [[The Five Precepts|pancha sila (Five Precepts)]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Faith at work==\nThe movement to help laity apply their faith to daily life has been divided into three eras by [[David W. Miller]] in ''God at Work''.<ref>Donald W. Miller, ''God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement'' (Oxford, 2006), Contents.</ref>\n:* The Social Gospel Era (c. 1890s\u20141945)\n:* The Ministry of the Laity Era (c.1946\u20141985)\n:* The Faith at Work Era (c. 1985\u2014Present)\n\n===Social Gospel===\nThe [[Social Gospel]] sought to reform society by the application of biblical principles. Its major proponents were all clergy: [[Washington Gladden]], [[Charles Monroe Sheldon]], and [[Walter Rauschenbusch]]. They were better in diagnosing society's ills than finding remedies.<ref>Ronald Cedric White, Charles Howard Hopkins, ''The Social Gospel: Religion and Reform in Changing America'' (Temple University, 1976). xviii.</ref> The Social Gospel reached its peak just prior to World War I, a war that contradicted its optimism about Christianizing society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldvieweyes.org/strauss-docs.html|title=WorldViewEyes -> strauss-docs|website=www.worldvieweyes.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Social Gospel was promulgated by the preaching, writing, and other efforts of clergy on behalf of the laity rather than by the laity themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ushistory.org/us/38e.asp|title=Religious Revival: The \"Social Gospel\" [ushistory.org]|first=|last=ushistory.org|website=www.ushistory.org}}</ref> In the early 1930s, the Social Gospel was described as \"a preacher's gospel.  It has not been the church's gospel. The laity have little share in it.\" Many were not aware what their clergy believed.<ref>Charles C. Morrison  ''The Social Gospel and The Christian Cultus,'' (Harper & Brothers, 1933), 42.</ref>\n\nMost scholars hold that the Social Gospel movement peaked between 1900 and World War I. There is less agreement about when and why the decline happened.<ref>[https://www.boundless.com/u-s-history/textbooks/boundless-u-s-history-textbook/the-gilded-age-1870-1900-20/urban-reform-153/the-social-gospel-818-9270/ Boundless. \"The Social Gospel.\" ''Boundless U.S. History''. Boundless, 14 Nov. 2014. Retrieved 16 Jan. 2015 from boundless.com]</ref>\n\n===Ministry of the Laity===\nThe Ministry of the Laity in daily life premise was stated by Howard Grimes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talbot.edu/ce20/educators/protestant/lewis_grimes/|title=Lewis Howard Grimes|website=Biola University}}</ref> in his ''The Rebirth of the Laity''.\n\"Although it is not alone through our daily work that we exercise our call, there is a special sense in which we do so in that area, since so much of our lives are spent in our occupations as lawyer, doctor, manual laborer, skilled craftsmen, housewife, domestic servant, student, serviceman.\"<ref>Howard Grimes, ''The Rebirth of the Laity'' (Abingdon, 1962), 95.</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Dean Reber of the [[Auburn Theological Seminary]] wrote a retrospective of the Ministry of the Laity era based on research and survey. His research participants were women and men in equal numbers, aged 20 to 60, from six denominations. Reber found that \"all were really interested to link faith with their daily life and work.\" However, in his survey, Reber found that little had been done in the six denominations to enable laity to make this link. He observed a \"preoccupation with activities inside the church,\" as well as a lack of literature and programs on the subject. For these reasons, attempts to link faith and daily life \"fizzled out.\"<ref>Robert E. Reber, \"Vocation and Vision: a New Look at the Ministry of the Laity\" in ''Religious Education: the official journal of the Religious Education Association'', 83:3, 1988. 402-411.</ref>\n\nFor Miller, \"hindsight suggests that the institutional church and its leaders never fully embraced or understood lay ministry\". Therefore, they stopped promoting the \"ministry of the laity\" concept to their members.<ref>Donald W. Miller, ''God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement'' (Oxford University Press, USA, 2006), 47.</ref>\n\n===Faith at Work===\nMiller deems \"Faith at Work\" to be \"a bona fide social movement and here to stay.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/God-Work-History-Promise-Movement-ebook/dp/B00OPJ8QOY/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1420320145&sr=1-1&keywords=9780199886234|title=God at Work: The History and Promise of the Faith at Work Movement|first=search|last=results|date=14 December 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Amazon}}</ref> Unlike earlier movements, business people (from evangelical and mainline Protestant denominations, Roman Catholics, Jews, Buddhists, and unaffiliated) initiated the faith at work movement and support it because they want to connect their work and their faith. Management training often includes a faith dimension.<ref>Laura Nash and Scott McLennan, ''Church on Sunday, Work on Monday'' (Jossey-Bass, 2001), xxi-xxiv.</ref>\n\nExamples of various kinds of faith at work initiatives follow:\n\n* The Theology of Work Project is an independent international organization that produces materials for \"workplace Christians\" to teach them what the Bible and the Christian faith can contribute to ordinary work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theologyofwork.org/about/|title=About - Theology of Work|first=Theology of|last=Work|website=www.theologyofwork.org}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The National Center for the Laity (NCL) grew out of the 1977 \"A Chicago Declaration of Christian Concern.\"<ref name=\"catholiclabor.org\"/> It propagates the [[Second Vatican Council]]'s teaching about laity's vocation as \"daily work.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/History%20of%20NCL.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923200855/http://www.catholiclabor.org/NCL%20Inititiative/History%20of%20NCL.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-23 }}</ref> The NCL's primary voice is ''Initiatives: In Support of Christians in the World''. In its January 2015 issue, ''Initiatives'' listed worldwide initiatives taken by laity in connecting faith and work.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* C12 Group offers training laced with Christian principles for CEO/Owners by monthly all-day meetings led by former CEOs. In its name, \"C\" stands for Christ, \"12\" stands for its ideal training group size. Group membership costs up to $1,450 per month. Some 1,500 Christian CEO/Owners belong to C12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c12group.com/.|title=Home - C12 Group|website=www.c12group.com}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Princeton University Faith & Work Initiative develops resources regarding ethics and vocation at work. It disseminates its learnings by programs for students, academics, and leaders in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeton.edu/faithandwork/|title=www.princeton.edu/faithandwork/|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Industrial Christian Fellowship helps its \"members and others to live out their faith at their work\" by research and publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icf-online.org/|title=www.icf-online.org|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n* The Christian Association of Business Executives (CABE) \"exists to Inform, Inspire and Influence Christian business people from all church backgrounds and all types of business, as they seek to live out their faith day to day.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cabe-online.org/|title=Home - Christian Association of Business Executives|website=Christian Association of Business Executives}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Workplace as a mission field===\nSome faith at work initiatives focus not on work itself but on the workplace as a \"mission field.\" In this \"business as missions\" concept, faith at work means \"reaching people for Christ in the marketplace\", people that career missionaries could not reach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/business-professionals-advance-gode28099s-kingdom/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118195643/http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/business-professionals-advance-gode28099s-kingdom/ |archivedate=2015-01-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://swbts.edu/campus-news/news-releases/businessmen-view-marketplace-as-mission-field/|title=Businessmen view marketplace as mission field - Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary|website=swbts.edu}}</ref> For example, Member Mission \"teaches the baptized to see themselves as missionaries out in the world in each of their daily places\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.membermission.org/about-member-mission/|title=About Member Mission|date=6 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lay brother]]\n* [[Laypeople (disambiguation)]]\n* [[La\u00efcit\u00e9]]\n* [[Expert]]\n* [[Jargon]]\n* [[Mumin]]\n* [[Upasaka]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n=== Roman Catholic theology of the laity ===\n* Burkhart, Ernst and L\u00f3pez D\u00edaz, Javier (2010, 2011, 2013), ''Vida cotidiana y santidad en la ense\u00f1anza de san Josemar\u00eda'', 3 vols., Madrid: Rialp\n* {{Citation|last = Congar|first = Yves Marie-Joseph|title = Lay people in the Church: a study for a theology of laity|year = 1957|publisher = Christian Classics|ISBN = 978-0870611148|location = Westminster}}\n* {{Citation|last = Dani\u00e9lou|first = Jean Guenol\u00e9-Marie|title = Saintet\u00e9 et action temporelle|language = French|publisher = Descl\u00e9e|year = 1955|location = Paris-Tournai}}\n* {{Citation|last = Philips|first = G.|title = Le r\u00f4le du la\u00efcat dans l'\u00c9glise|language = French|year = 1954|location = Paris-Tournai}}\n* {{Citation|last = Spiazzi|first = Raimondo|title = La Missione dei Laici|language = Italian|location = Rome|year = 1951}}\n* Thils, G. (1946), ''Th\u00e9ologie des r\u00e9alit\u00e9s terrestres,'' Paris.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_INDEX.HTM The Code of Canon Law] (Roman Catholic Church)\n* [http://www.sacred-texts.com/asia/rsv/rsv08.htm The Religions of South Vietnam] in Faith and Fact: V. [[Buddhism in Vietnam]] (Section E. Definitions and Explanation of Buddhist Terms)\n* Tanner, S., [http://www.utlm.org/onlineresources/paidclergy.htm Do Mormon Leaders Receive Financial Support?]\n* Gibbs, M., [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222122712/http://vesper.org/vwp/wp-content/uploads/GibbsLectureStrongLaity3FLAME.pdf \"The Development of a Strong and Committed Laity\"]\n\n{{Catholic laity}}\n{{Christianity footer}}\n\n[[Category:Religious terminology]]\n", "name_user": "81.103.177.108", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laity"}
{"title_page": "Cherthala (State Assembly constituency)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 103\n| name                   = Cherthala <br/> \u0d1a\u0d47\u0d7c\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d32\n| existence              = 2011 - present\n| reserved               = None\n| current mla            = [[P. Thilothaman]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Alappuzha district|Alappuzha]]\n| electorate             =   2,04,830 (2016)\n| self governed segments =Cherthala Municipality\nCherthala South Panchayat\nKadakkarappally Panchayat\nKanjikkuzhi Panchayat\nMuhamma Panchayat\nPattanakkad Panchayat\nThanneermukkam Panchayat\nVayalar Panchayat \n}}  \n\n'''Cherthala State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d1a\u0d47\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d32 \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Alappuzha (Lok Sabha constituency)|Alappuzha Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://alappuzha.nic.in/legislative-assembly-constituencies\n |website     = alappuzha.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Alappuzha district, Kerala\n |accessdate  = 11 March 2020\n}}</ref>The current MLA is [[P. Thilothaman]]\n==See also==\n* [[Cherthala]]\n* [[Alappuzha district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Alappuzha district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 103\n| name                   = Cherthala <br/> \u0d1a\u0d47\u0d7c\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d32\n| existence              = 2011 - present\n| reserved               = None\n| current mla            = [[P. Thilothaman]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Alappuzha district|Alappuzha]]\n| electorate             =   2,04,830 (2016)\n| self governed segments = \n}}  \n\n'''Cherthala State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d1a\u0d47\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d32 \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Alappuzha (Lok Sabha constituency)|Alappuzha Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://alappuzha.nic.in/legislative-assembly-constituencies\n |website     = alappuzha.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Alappuzha district, Kerala\n |accessdate  = 11 March 2020\n}}</ref>\n==See also==\n* [[Cherthala]]\n* [[Alappuzha district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Alappuzha district]]\n", "name_user": "Aswin8", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cherthala_(State_Assembly_constituency)"}
{"title_page": "Dexter R. Voisin", "text_new": "'''Dexter Rommell Voisin''' is an American professor, social work scientist, author, licensed psychotherapist,.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/america-the-beautiful-and-violent/9780231184410|title=Columbia University Press, America the Beautiful and Violent|last=|first=|date=|website=Columbia University Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and public speaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allamericanspeakers.com/speakers/440223/Dexter-R.-Voisin|title=AAE Speakers, Dexter R. Voisin|last=|first=|date=|website=All American Entertainment (AAE)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> whose work focuses on the impact of structural violence on the psychosocial development of racial and sexual minorities<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hong, Voisin, Kim, Allen-Meares, Espelage|title=Pathways from peer victimization to sexual risk-taking behavior among African American adolescents in Chicago's Southside.|url=|journal=Psychology of Violence|volume=9|issue=1|pages=88\u201397|doi=10.1037/vio0000164|year=2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Voisin |first=Dexter R.|title=Exposure to Community Violence and Sexual Behaviors Among African American Youth: Testing Multiple Pathways |journal=[[Behavioral Medicine (journal)|Behavioral Medicine]] |volume=44 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201327 |doi=10.1080/08964289.2016.1189394 |pmid=27223490 |year=2018}}</ref> and the factors that promote resiliency despite embedded inequalities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/scientific-contributions/2122318498_Dexter_R_Voisin|title=Dexter R. Voisin's research works {{!}} University of Chicago, IL (UC) and other places|website=ResearchGate|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=America the Beautiful and Violent: Black Youth and Neighborhood Trauma in Chicago|last=Voisin|first=Dexter R.|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2019|isbn=9780231184410|location=|pages=312}}</ref> He is currently the Dean at the University of Toronto's Factor-Inwentash Faculty of Social (FIFSW),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialwork.utoronto.ca/about-us/deans-message/|title=Dean's Message|last=|first=|date=|website=Factor-Inwentash Faculty of Social Work|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which is the oldest school of social work in Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oasw.org/Public/Social_Work_Week_Tab/History_of_Social_Work_in_Ontario.aspx|title=History of Social Work in Ontario|last=|first=|date=|website=Ontario Association of Social Workers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and is ranked #1 nationally and #2 globally among all schools of social work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cwur.org/2017/subjects.php#Social%20Work|title=Rankings by Subject - 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=Center for World University Rankings (CWUR)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also holds the Sandra Rotman Chair in Social Work at the [[University of Toronto]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialwork.utoronto.ca/about-us/endowed-chairs/#rotman|title=Endowed Chairs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factor-Inwentash Faculty of Social Work|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which is ranked 18th among all universities globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/university-toronto|title=Times Higher Education, University of Toronto|last=|first=|date=|website=Times Higher Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Prior to his appointment as Dean in July, 2019 he was a Professor at the University of Chicago's School of Social of Social Service Administration for two decades and Director and Co-Director at the STI/HIV Intervention Network and the Chicago Center for HIV Elimination, also at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialwork.utoronto.ca/profiles/dexter-voisin/|title=Dexter R. Voisin|last=|first=|date=|website=Factor-Inwentash Faculty of Social Work|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is recognized as one of the most influential and cited Black scholars in premier schools of social work in North America.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huggins-Hoyt, K. Y., Holosko, M. J., Briggs, H. E., & Barner, J. R.|first=|date=2015|title=Citation impact scores of top African American scholars in social work schools: The story behind the data.|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ1048334|journal=Research on Social Work Practice|volume=25(1)|pages=164-170|via=}}</ref> His expertise and research findings have been frequently cited by numerous members of the international, national, and local media. He is the author of the book ''American the beautiful and violent: Black youth and neighborhood trauma in Chicago'', which is published by Columbia University Press<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/america-the-beautiful-and-violent/9780231184410|title=Columbia University Press|last=|first=|date=|website=Columbia University Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n== Selected media coverage ==\nVoisin's expertise and research findings have been frequently cited by numerous members of the international, national, and local media:\n\n* \"Concerns about China\u2019s influence don\u2019t end at the WHO, experts say. They\u2019re calling for sweeping reviews of international bodies,\" Toronto Star, April 16, 2020<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nuttal, Jeremy; Chiu, Joanna|first=|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/14/concerns-about-chinas-influence-dont-end-at-the-who-experts-say-theyre-calling-for-sweeping-reviews-of-international-bodies.html|title=Concerns about China\u2019s influence don\u2019t end at the WHO, experts say. They\u2019re calling for sweeping reviews of international bodies|date=April 15, 2020|work=Toronto Star|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \u